skos:Concept.skos:definition: Hautbois du Couserans, France
Instrument with free reeds (sort of harmonium) invented by Christian Dietz around 1830
Lamellophone played by Bwa, Ngbele, Mbuja, Budeu & Makere peoples
One-stringed tube fiddle of the Makonde people in south-eastern Africa (Mozambique, Tanzania)
Idiophone drum from the Fulsé people in the Pobé Mengao department of Burkina Faso. Made from a gourd cut in two and carved out
Kettle drum from the Tamasheq people in the Northern Gorom Gorom department of Burkina Faso

Compact large single-headed cylindrical drum with feet carved out of the base, and which is beated with a stick. Played by of the Mbosi-Koyo people in the Cuvette region of Republic of the Congo. Geometrical engravings decorate the body. Used in the Odaki (OdaKé) lovers dance, and in the Ekongo warriors dance

Guimbarde originaire du Cambodge. Il en existe deux sortes : la première, en métal, possède une languette hétéroglotte alourdie à son extrémité par une boule de cire. La deuxième, fabriquée en bambou, a une languette idioglotte

Indonesian fiddle from Bolaang Mongondon (North Sulawesi), on the east coast of Sulawesi, and Halmahera, Maluku. Its soundboard is half a coconut shell, usually covered with a membrane of buffalo bladder

Spike fiddle of the Batak Karo and Batak Toba areas in North Sumatra, Indonesia. Its spike and neck are made of wood and its gourdshaped body of coconut shell, 8 to 15 cm in diameter. The top of the neck may be decorated with a carved scroll. Two strings
Balafon, played in ensemble (solo, bass, accompaniments) of the Nzime people in the Sangha region, close to the Cameroun border
Hautbois cylindrique à anche double idioglotte, présent en Chine
A type of Armenian folk cello
General term for single string fiddle played in central India by tribal groups
Two-string fiddle of the Han Chinese; resonator is coconut or gourd, covered with wooden soundboard; it has laterally inserted tuning pegs
Small side-blown wooden horn of the Moosé and Nuni people, Burkina. The mouthpiece is cut in the outer curve of the horn

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: Organo a rulli / Organetto di Barberia

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Polish folk double bass; size not standarized

A kind of trumpet (straight labrosone) with a conical profile, made from a trunk of a young tree that is cut along in two halves, then each is hollowed, and finally both are put back together with the help of pitch; formerly used for apotropaic purposes (while making the ritual uproar) and signalling (shepherds, fishermen, firefighters, to signal the beginning of rituals and ceremonies); nowadays as part of folk revival; a symbol of Cassubians' ethnic identity (Kaszuby, the region of Poland)

Calebash drum from the Yana people of Burkina Faso. Made from a round gourd of which the top is cut off and which is covered with a small goatskin membrane. It is called Binderi or Binha by the Moosè people of Burkina Faso
Goblet shaped drum from the Gan people in Burkina
Elongated hourglass drum from the Winnè people in Burkina Faso
Term used in Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines for the western violin, tuned like a viola
Europese volksvedel met een blaas als resonator
Flûte oblique d'Arménie, d'origine pastorale et semblable au blur turc

Traditional Andean, lowland and Central American single-skin frame drum with handle. The mestizo bombo, e.g. the Argentinean and Chilean bombo is a double-skin cylindrical drum. The Argentinean 'bombo legüero' is a barrel drum
Cornemuse du Val d'Aran, sans bourdon et à anche simple
Large cylindrical footed drum from the Koyo and Banguele of the Cuvette region (Makoua) in the Republic of Congo. Used fot popular festivitie

Idioglot transverse clarinet of the Bissa people in Burkina Faso. Made from a hollowed-out millet stalk. It has two small gourd resonators with side windows placed over the ends of the stalk. It usually has a finger-hole at the distal end which may be stopped by the left thumb. http://inconstantsol.blogspot.be/2014/01/musique-bisa-de-haute-volta-rec-1961.html
Tuvan four-stringed spike tube fiddle
In Balinese culture, the Calung is actually a metallophonic instrument that has a one-octave range, and is generally utilized to play mid-range melodies

Wooden transverse flute from the Fulbe people in Burkina Fasothe Fulbe people in Burkina Faso, more specifically of the riimaaybe, 'descendants of the captives', belonging to a specific stratos of fulbe society, 'dispossessed of their cultural origins after having been captured during wars or raids, or purchased from neighbouring posers by the Fulbe... The descendants of the captives work the land in direct usufruct. The musical practices of the different social groups remain clearly differentiated. The riimaaybe musicians are more or less seasonal specialists, they only play for their own festivities, well distinct from those of the Fulbe'
'Flute of the conqueror'; end blown sculptured flute from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Two- or three-stringed spike fiddle of Georgia
Fiddle of Rajastan, India. A pear-shaped, waisted belly, completely covered with skin, gradually tapering off into a hollowed-out neck of approximately the same length as the belly
One-stringed fiddle of West African origin, used in Cape Verde
Hautbois du Bigorre, France

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 管和弦一起发音的羽管键琴

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Folk fiddle with a clog as resonator from Sweden
Vietnamese two-string fiddle, resonator made of coconut shell
Vietnamese two-string fiddle, similar to Chinese erhu
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Kô people in Burkina Faso
Single-string fiddle of the Bukidnon people of the southern Philippines
Talking drum (double-headed hourglass drum; variable tension drum) from the Bobo people in Burkina Faso
A musical tool used to make the so-called musical racket; nowadays used as percussion instrument in folk bands in Kaszuby (Cassubia) Poland, and is a symbol of the region's musical identity
Musical bow of the Bissa people of Burkina Faso. It has a metal string and a resonator made of a calabash cut in two. The top part of the calabas may be attached to the upper part of the bow
Long-necked fretted fiddle from North India and Pakistan; resonator like that of a sarangi (as opposed to the esraj)
Flûte originaire du Laos et du Vietnam, similaire au bawu
Balafo with 14 lamels arranged on a strongly curved base from the Bwa people in Burkina faso
Term for a North-African bamboo duct flute

A type of drum played with both bare hands. It is in widespread use primarily in Mali and Guinea among the Maninka and Susu peoples, and also in neighbouring Senegal, Côte d'Ivoire and Burkina Faso; it is also perhaps the most popular African drum outside the African continent
Balafo with 14 to 18 lamels arranged on a cruved base, from the Dagara people in Burkina Faso. Called Gyilli in Ghana
Kettle drum from the Gouin eople in Burkina Faso played with two wooden sticks
A North African term for an oblique rim-blown flute
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Bwa people in Burkina Faso
[tro] Generic term for fiddles in Cambodja
Three-string spike fiddle from Cambodja, resembles the Javanese rebab
Two-string spike fiddle from Cambodja, resembles the Thai so u with a resonator of coconut
Hautbois arménien, l'anche double est appelée 'gamish'
Basic component of traditional folk bands in the south of the Beskid Żywiecki region, Poland
Single-string spike fiddle of the Bissa in Burkina Faso

Bambou transverse flute from the Fulbe people in Burkina Faso (made from a millet stalk), about 40 to 50 cm in length. These days, musicians prefer to have tube of forged iron, which does not go out of tune, and hardly wears out. The instrument is played obliquely so as to compensate for the absence of a prepared embouchure. the flute has 3 to 4 playing holes; the flautist can however obtain intermediate tones by fractional fingering
Vessel rattle of the Mobsi-Makwa people of Republic of the Congo. Made of a small calebash, of which the neck is closed with a cork
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Single-string spike tube fiddle of the Baganda in Uganda; often decorated with a tuft of goat hair at the top of the neck

One- or two-stringed archaic spike fiddle of the Iban of Sarawak, Borneo. Its soundbox is half a gourd or coconut shell, covered with animal skin. It exists in a simple form, without any decoration, and in a more elaborate form, where the top of the neck expands into a large disc carved into a floral pattern. The performer places the body of the instrument between his toes while sitting down, the knees bent outward and the soles of the feet together. The strings are moistened to produce the proper sound. The convex bow made of wood or bamboo is held in the right hand. There are specimens in the Museum Volkenkunde in Leiden, the Metropolitan Museum in New York, the Musée des Instruments de Musique in Brussels, the Sarawak Museum in Kuching and the Musée d'ethnographie de Neuchâtel
Two-stringed tube fiddle of the Han Chinese
Two-stringed tube fiddle from Guangdong or Fujian, with wooden tubular resonator and wooden soundboard
Long-neck fretted fiddle from Bengal (India and Bangladesh). Soundboard pear-shaped and waisted
Rattle made of a rectangular flat dried fruit, used by the Teke-Ngangoulou people of the Plateaux region in Republic of the Congo to accompany their dances

Idioglot transverse clarinet from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso. Made from a hollowed-out millet stalk. To be compared with the Bumpan of the Bissa people in Burkina Faso, but without the small gourd resonators over the ends of the stalk
Played in the vertical position (hung over the shoulder on a string or leaned on the knee); players applied side string shortening (the so-called fingernail technique)
Single-string spike fiddle with two holes in the soundtable from Zaghawa and Kanembu and other people in north-eastern and north-western Chad
Pear-shaped fiddle of Bulgaria with three strings; some have sympathetic strings
Cornemuse de Galice
Double-headed ylindrical drum of the Yana and Moosè people in Burkina Faso. 'Gangango' means 'drum' in Moorè language. The generic name in West and North African cultures is 'Ganga'
Double-headed cylindrical drum from the Gulmancé people in Burkina Faso
Double-headed cylindrical drum from the Tamasheq people in Burkina Faso
One- or two-stringed spike fiddle of the Dayak in Borneo
Spike fiddle (of the Toraja) in Sulawesi Selatan (South Sulawesi)
Spike fiddle of northern Afghanistan, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan; resonator may be spherical like the kamanche or made from a square tin can
Single-string spike fiddle of the Maghreb; resembles the goge
Single-string spike fiddle of Bénin
Single-string spike fiddle with gourd resonator from Western Africa, term used by Hausa and Yoruba people in ia Nigeria and Niger
Double terra cotta kettledrum from the Siamou people in Burkina Faso
Balafo with 15 lamels from the Turka people in Burkina Faso
[gonje] Single-string spike fiddle of the Dagbamba people of Ghana
Double-headed cylindrical drum from the Winnè people in Burkina Faso
Wooden goblet drum from the Samogo people in Burkina Faso
Large double-headed cylindrical drum from the Nuni people of Burkina Faso
Small double-headed cylindrical drum from the Nuni people of Burkina Faso
Elongated hourglass drum from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Ancient three-string fiddle of Russia and Belarussia with a pear-shaped body
Long elongated hourglass drum of about 130 cm from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Long elongated hourglass drum of about 100 cm from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Two-stringed plucked spike lute with a loose cylindrical bridge (piece of bambou stem) from the Hausa people in Burkina Faso. It has a half-calabash soundbox
Single-string fiddle of Yugoslavia, often with horse-head decoration on top of neck
Corn stalk fiddle of Bosnia and Serbia
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Winnè people in Burkina Faso
Two-stringed spike fiddle from Korea with wooden soundboard

Norwegian folk fiddle, resembling the violin, with 4 melody strings and 4 sympathetic strings; often elaborately decorated with geometrical and vegetal designs, with the head of a Norwegian lion or dragon on the pegbox

Pedal accordion, bellows connected to the instrument with a two-piece pipe. After World War I the accordion became a popular component of polish folk bands (together with the violin and the drum); the pedal type being especially popular in Mazovia on the right side of the Vistula river (the region of Kurpie and the area of Garwolin), to some degree also in Podlasie (Podlachia)

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 黑克尔管（上低音双簧管）

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Balafo with 14 lamels from the Lobi people in Burkina Faso
Small end-blown wooden flute (15 to 20 cm) from the Bissa people in Burkina Faso
Wooden griot lute from the Fulbé people of Burkina Faso
Hautbois sri lankais

skos:Concept.skos:altLabel: Violí amb trompa, Violí amb botzina

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: Effetto sonoro degli zoccoli di cavallo
Tambor amb forma de rellotge de sorra
Tambor en forma de reloj de arena

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Two-stringed spike fiddle from China, with a resonator made from gourd; the pegbox of the one from MIM Phoenix has a 'fantasy' wooden design
Fiddle from Myanmar; shaped like a violin, often a highly decorated pegbox; has become obsolete now
Ancient Chinese lute. NB: in Metropolitan Museum this is described as a fiddle as it comes with a bow!
Generic term for Chinese fiddle, literally 'barbarian string instrument'
Fiddle of the Uyghur people (mainly from the Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region in western China); highly decorated and often with a bird (nightingale) on the pegbox
Three-stringed fiddle from the Wends or Sorbs of eastern Germany and Slavonic countries; soundboard is waisted, the instrument looks like a primitive violin
Single-string tube fiddle of Burundi with a soundbox made of cow horn
Two-stringed fiddle of the Tuva people of Siberia, often with horse head on pegbox
Turkish fiddle, originally a gourd spike-fiddle (type of kabak = 'gourd fiddle')
Single-string spike fiddle of the Touareg in northern Africa, with a calabash resonator and often two soundholes in the membrane
Harp-lute from the Gogo people in Tanzania, consisting of up to 14 metal strings running over an oblique bridge. The resonator is made of a calebash
Two-string fiddle of the Han Chinese, especially from the north; smaller than erhu
Four-string spike fiddle of Iraq; 'joza' means coconut, and refers to the coconut resonator
Wooden sculpted flute (30 to 40 cm) with two fingerholes used to accompany the masked dances of the Nuni people from Burkina Faso

Monochord calabash half-spike lute of the Fulbe people in Burkina Faso, more specifically of the riimaaybe, 'descendants of the captives', belonging to a specific stratos of fulbe society, 'dispossessed of their cultural origins after having been captured during wars or raids, or purchased from neighbouring posers by the Fulbe... The descendants of the captives work the land in direct usufruct. The musical practices of the different social groups remain clearly differentiated. The riimaaybe musicians are more or less seasonal specialists, they only play for their own festivities, well distinct from those of the Fulbe' Sandrine Loncke, Burkina Faso. The voice of the Fulbe / La voix des Peuls, CD Le Chant du monde CNR 274 1079, 1997, CD notes, p. 25-26, 35-36
North African term for an oblique rim-blown flute
Chad ensemble of calebashes, the biggest one used as recipient filled with water in which the two smaller ones are beaten
Wooden sculpted flute (ca. 25 cm) with two fingerholes from the Nuni people from Burkina Faso
Anthropomorphic fiddle of the Holo and Suku people of southwestern DR Congo and northern Angola; the head is the pegbox; the soundboard is a thin wooden board
One-stringed tube fiddle of the Chewa people in southern and central Malawi; the projecting tip of the neck acts as string-holder; Werner notes the term chimwenyuwenyu on Likoma island in Lake Malawi
Three-stringed fiddle of the Lunda and Chokwe people of southern DR Congo, northeastern Angola and northern Zambia
Short-necked fiddle with large round soundboard from Rajasthan, played by the Manghaniyar caste
Fiddle from Armenia, with rectangular soundboard and 3 or 4 strings
Spike fiddle of Iran with a spherical body often inlaid with mother-of-pearl or bone; formerly three strings, modern instruments have four
Flûte oblique égyptienne en bambou à 3 sections et 6 trous de jeu
Rectangular 'raft' rattle from the Mijikenda people in Kenya, consisting of a tray-shaped box made from made of straw stems bound together, with seeds inside

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 科曼拿（甘美兰香蕉型铜鼓）

skos:Concept.skos:definition: (i) Short-necked fiddle from Turkey with a bottle-shaped soundboard and three strings; (ii) in Western Turkey the kemençe is similar to the Greek lyra with a pear shaped soundboard and three strings
The kemençe with a bottle-shaped soundboard played by Greek refugees from the Turkish Black Sea coast; also called Pontic lyra
Mongolian two-stringed spike tube fiddle, mostly used in ensembles
Single-string half spike fiddle from the Daza and Teda of Tibesti and Ouaddai in Chad

Three-string fiddle of Madhya Pradesh in India with a wooden soundbox; however, the kikirs in the FF database in M+ all have one string and a soundbox made from ceramic material (see description TUA-326); on the internet (see sources), the kingri is also said to have a resonator box made from unglazed pottery (New Grove)
Sanza of the Teke, Kongo and Bembe people of the Republic of the Congo. Five to eight lamellae in metal or bamboo, mounted on a box or a board
Cylindrical friction drum of the Kongo people of the Bouenza region (Mouyondzi) in the Republic of Congo, Used to accompany religious and laic songs
A term which in its many linguistic variant forms denotes a number of types of lamellophones found mainly in the Congo's and bordering countries

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 罕用语](旧时舞蹈教师用的)小提琴

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Large side blown anthopomorphic wooden natural trumpet of the Kongo-Bembe people of Republic of the Congo
Apache fiddle made from a hollowed-out agave stalk, with two or three strings; often decorated with geometrical or natural designs; also called tsi edo atl
Fiddle from Japan, derived from the Chinese huqin
Small wooden sculpted flute (12 to 15 cm) with fingerholes, in the form of a stylised bird, from the Nuni people of Burkina Faso
Japanese indigenous spike box fiddle, usually with three strings (but sometimes the highest string is doubled)
Harp-lute from the Bwa and Gouin people in Burkina Faso
Two-stringed calabash lute from the Bissa people in Burkina Faso
Sanza with 6 lamels from the Bissa people in Burkina Faso

Triangual frame zither from the Lobi people of Burkina Faso, with several gourds attached as resonator, including one at the point of V of the arm. Six to nine strings. May have a metal buzzer at the end of the arm
Gulmantché term for the one-stringed spike fiddle in Burkina Faso

A polish bagpipe from Podhale region. A mouth blown instrument; four voices; has a short triple chanter-drone pipe (5+1 fingerholes) and a long drone pipe ending in a hyperbolic bell (of a clarinet type); all pipes with cylindrical bores; bag made from a goat's whole skin; formerly played solo (by shepherds, wandering musicians), nowadays in folk revival, sometimes included in Podhale bands. The ability to build and play the Podhale bagpipe, or goat, were included on the National List of Intangible Cultural Heritage

A polish bagpipe with low tuning and elegiac sound; formerly used during the ritual part of the wedding ceremony together with mazanki, after World War II reactivated in the S. Moniuszko Music School in Zbąszyń and in the folk revival

A bagpipe with 16th c. roots; the biggest of Polish bagpipes with the lowest tuning and an elegiac sound; traditional element of folk bands in west Greater Poland (along with violins and, after World War I, an E-flat clarinet)
Three-stringed spike fiddle of Okinawa, Japan. The resonator is half a coconut shell, covered with snake skin
Conical drum of the Teke-Kukuya people of the republic of Congo
Single-string spike fiddle of the Hausa in Nigeria, smaller than goge
Wooden lute from the Moosè people in Burkina Faso

A portable xylophone of the Sara, Barma and neighbouring peoples of southern Chad. The keys are strung together each above a gourd resonator, which can be either curved or staight and is fitted with a mirliton made of a fish bladder, bat's wing or spider's web
Single-string spike fiddle of the Susu people in Guinea and Sierra Leone
Single-string fiddle of the southern Philippines
Single-string fiddle from Albania, similar to the Gusle; in New Grove spelled as Lahutë

A kind of horn (conical profile), made from a branch that is cut along in two halves, then each is hollowed, and finally both are put back together with the help of pitch and metal hoops; formerly used as a signal instrument (mainly in herding); since 19th c. used during Advent and watchnight service on Christmas Eve (mainly in north-east and east regions of Poland); nowadays as part of folk revival
Short-necked fiddle from Greece, with a pear-shaped body and two D-shaped soundholes in the soundboard; usually three strings
Side blown horn of the Bomitaba people in the Likouala region of Republic of the Congo. Made from an antilope horn
Three-string fiddle of the Ilonggot people of the northern Philippines
Generic term for several instruments in Madagascar; here it refers to fiddles from Madagascar
Musical bow from the Samo peopàle in Burkina Faso consisting of a string supported by a flexible wooden string bearer. A calebash is attached as resonator
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Gulmancé people in Burkina Faso
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from Burkina Faso and Ivory Coast
Wooden griot lute from the Fulbé people of Burkina Faso
Rudimentary xylophone of the Bomitaba people of the Likouala region in Republic of the Congo. Played on the ground, with 5 lamellae
Two-stringed tube fiddle from Guangxi and Ghuizhou provinces in China; the name means 'horse bone fiddle', the resonator is made of horse bone
[sekhankula] Single-string fiddle from southern Africa, mainly among Sotho people; it has a tin can resonator
Single-stringed spike fiddle from Ethiopia with a rhombus shaped resonator

Small fiddle of the Wielkopolska (Greater Poland), region of Poland. An instrument with medieval roots; before World War I used in Poland during the ritual part of the wedding (wedding feast) together with the wedding bagpipe (Kozioł weselny / Kozioł biały); after World War II reactivated in the S. Moniuszko Music School in Zbąszyń; now used in the folk revival, too. Almost entirely carved from one piece of wood; three strings; one of bridge's feet longer, going through an opening in the top plate and resting on the back plate, functioning as a soundpost
Single-string fiddle of the Kamba/Mijikenda people of Kenya
Single-string fiddle of the Guaycuru people in Chaco, Argentina

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 延音钢琴（可发出持续音）

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Hautbois cylindrique turc
Vessel rattle of the Teke-Ngangoulou people of the Plateaux region in Republic of the Congo. Made of a small calebash, filled with grains of which the neck is closed with a cork
Large conical drum from the Gan people in Burkina Faso
Fiddle (khuur) with horse head from Mongolia; two strings and trapezoid soundbox

Rattle of the Mbosi people in the Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo. Two or more small dried gourds are mounted on a stick and serve as vessel rattles. Used by the griot to accompany his praise songs

Vessel rattle made from a big dried longitudinal bean-like fruit, from the Teke-Kukuya people in the Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo. Called Oumouaka by the Pygmee people of Republic of the Congo
Iron double bell, often with a raphia woven handle from the Teke peoples in the Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo
Vessel rattle made from a big dried longitudinal bean-like fruit, from the Teke people in the Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo
One-stringed tube fiddle from Nyanja people in Mozambique; string is tuned with tuning loop around neck
Slit drum from the Kongo and Bembe peoples of the Congo's. Used to accompany the Mufueti or Masoko dance. It is crescent shaped, played in pairs, and associated with religious and magical practices
Single or double woven rattle with handle from the Kongo and Bembe people of the Bouenza region in the south of Republic of the Congo
Scraped slit stick of the Kongo, Bembe and Suku peoples of the Congo's. It is a hollowed stick or bamboo tube with a lengthwise slit
Spike fiddle from northern Sumatra from the Batak people
Hautbois droit ou courbe du Népal
Stick zither with a notched bridge, which supports its five strings in a plane at right angles to that of the string-bearer. Unique to the area of western central Africa
Vessel rattle made from a big dried longitudinal bean-like fruit, from the Teke-Nangoulou people in the Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo
Side blown horn of the Teke people in the Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo. Made from an antelope horn. Protects against lightning and serves as a means of communication
Side blown horn of the Kongo and Bembe people of the Bouenza region in the south of Republic of the Congo. Made from an antelope horn. 'Mvouri' = 'antelope'. Used to accompany songs calling for rain
Side blown antelope horn of the Mbosi and Kongo people of the Congo's

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: Piano in forma di tavolo da cucito

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Longitudinal wooden drum from the Kongo and Vili people of the Kouilou region (Pointe-Noire) in the Republic of the Congo. Played horizontally, with a handle carved in the wooden sound box. Used for the healing ritual called ' n'assi ', for popular festivities and also used for communication
Cylindrical drum from the Toussian people in Burkina Faso

Small double-skin barrel drum of the Kongo-Vili and Kongo-Bembe peoples of the Kouilou and Bouenza regions in the lower Republic of the Congo. Both skins (goath or antilope) are laced together over the sound box with woven chords
Cylindro-concial drum of the Konda and Yembe peoples of the DRC. The name is also used for the footed conical drum of the Kongo and Bembe peoples of the Republic of Congo
Small wooden sculpted flute with fingerholes, in the form of a stylised bird, from the Nuni people of Burkina Faso
Barrel drum of the Banda-Ngbugu in Central African Republic

Large single-headed barrel drum with feet carved out of the base, and which is beated with a stick. Played by the Mbosi-Makwa people in the Republic of the Congo. Used in the Amin celebration dance and lullaby. Cf. Angoho of the Mbosi-Koyo people
A common term (with many vairants) used generically for many kinds of drum among the numerous Bantu-speaking peoples of central, eastern-central and southern Africa
Portable eight plaque bass xylophone from the Bomitaba people of the Likouala region in the north of the Republic of the Congo

Five-string plucked lute of the Kongo-Bembe peoples of the Republic of the Congo. The 5 metal strings are tuned with large upright tuning pegs fitted with metal jingles. The strings are plucked with the thumb and forefinger of both hands. The instrument is used mainly to accompany singing
Bow lute (5 bows) of the Kongo-Bembe people of the Republic of Congo
Harp-lute from Burkina Faso. Seven or eight strings. The resonator is a half or three quarter calebash
Rattles made of small dried fruits strung to a strap, from the Mbosi-Makwa people in the Cuvette region of Republic of the Congo
Compact footed barrel drum from the Mbosi people of the Plateaux region in the Republic of the Congo.

Solid cylindrical (sometimes barrel or conical) drum (with or without feet carved out from the base) from the Teke-Ngangoulou people of the Plateau (Gamboma) region in the Republic of the Congo. Used to accompany songs in the ritual dances and popular festivities

Bow lute of the Teke people in Central Africa, the Congo's and Gabon. Five fibre strings are mounted almost perpendicular to a large sound box, on which geometrical decorations are engraved and burned. A buzzing effect is produced by metal jingles on the string-bearers
Lute from the Teke People in the Republic of Congo. Used to accompany ritual and popular dances
Animal horn with mouthpiece cut out on the outer curved side of the horn, with an additional whole which serves as a fingerhole. From the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Ox horn fiddle from the Buyi people in southern China, the resonator being of ox horn and the neck of wood
'Ox leg' two-stringed fiddle of the Dong people in Guizhou, south-western China (shape is that of an ox leg, hence the name)
Single-string fiddle (of the Songhay people?) of Mali; noteable performer Ali Farka Touré
General term in the Congos (RDC and RC) for a small slit-drum carved from a wooden stick

Rattle of the Kongo -Bembe and Kongo-Minkengue people in the Bouenza region of Republic of the Congo. Two or more small dried gourds are mounted on a stick and serve as vessel rattles. Used by the griot to accompany his praise songs
Bell of the Teke people in the Cuvette and Plateaux region of Republic of the Congo. Made of buffle horns

Small side blown horn of the Teke people in Gabon and the Republic of the Congo. Made from an antelope horn. Serves as a means of communication and to call the spirits of the ancestors. 'Ntsiemi' means 'horn' in the Teke language
Peul term for the one-stringed spike fiddle in Western Africa; note the soundhole in the soundbox, not in the soundboard
Bowl lyre of the Luo people from Kenya
Keyed fiddle from Scandinavia and northern Germany, with melody strings, bourdon strings and sympathetic strings; it plays an important role in Swedish folk music
Large bowl lyre of the Gusii people in Kenya, with large flat bridge
Vessel rattle of the Mobsi-Koyo people of Republic of the Congo. Made of a small calebash, of which the neck is closed with a cork
Plain cylindrical footed drum from the Mbosi-Koyo people of the Cuvette region (Owando) in the Republic of Congo. Used in a dance to celebrate the birth of twins called 'Okera'
Goblet drum from the Mbosi ans Makwa people of the Cuvette region (Makoua) in the Republic of the Congo. Used in the Ondzambé dance
Vessel rattle made from a big dried longitudinal bean-like fruit, from the Teke people in the Republic of Congo. Called Otsara by the Pygmee people of Republic of the Congo
Single-string spike fiddle of the Luo people of Kenya
Large wooden drum with five big pegs, held in a vertical playing position. From the Bobo people in Burkina Faso

Small single-headed square frame drum from the Teke people in the Republic of the Congo. The skin is nailed to a robust wooden frame. Held between the legs, the pitch can be changed by the pressure of the heel on the skin. Used to accompany the danse 'okilidzéké' of the young people. Also used in the 1920's in the maringa, an urban music style attributed amonst other to the Loango region on the French Congolese coast, and described as 'Europeanized' since it included also accordion and rhythms borrowed from polkas, marches, hymns, etc. The patenge is also played to accompany the rumba
Single-string spike fiddle from Manipur, north-eastern India without tuning peg (string is directly attached to the neck); it comes with a large iron bow with bells on it
Hautbois du Cambodge

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 高压气体使弦发音的钢琴

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A seasonal, polish folk instrument, made in the spring; would become porous and unplayable when it dried out; formerly a signal instrument (used by shepherds), often played by children, nowadays sometimes made as a music toy; body made from a spirally rolled piece of willow bark, fastened with a thorn ('przetyczka'); it should have a double reed ('bekas'), also made of willow bark, in the inlet
Spike tube fiddle from Tibet/Bhutan, with a resonator made of wood, metal or ivory; it has two to four strings
Single-string fiddle of the Pulluvan in Kerala, south India. The neck is glued to the soundbox and starts like a crescent which continues into a neck and ends in the pegbox
Clarinette indonésienne
Long fiddle from Lithuania, with a bladder as resonator, over which run the strings; it is played vertically, standing on the ground

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 喷气式管风琴 motion by gas jet

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Orgue à bouche du peuple Hmong
Two-stringed fiddle of the Karakalpak, Kazakh and Kirghiz people of Central Asia; resonator is a deeply carved out ladle, the bottom half is covered with skin
Mâchoire racle
A term for various chordophones, both fiddles and lutes; within the Formalized Fiddle it may refer to the Javanese rabab, the Arabic box spike fiddle, and the north African rabab
Spike fiddle from the Arab world; may refer to both the spike bowl fiddle and the quadrangular spike fiddle
Portugese fiddle resembling the western violin, used in Brazil during feasts

Kettle drum from the Yana people in Burkina Faso. Made of a calebash of which the top has been cut off and covered with a membrane. To be compared with the Bendré, but the skin glued to the calebash covers a bigger part of the resonator. Unlike the Bendré there are no cords to stretch the skin

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: 舌头放在唇间发出的声音？

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Spike fiddle from Rajasthan and Gujarat, north-west India; the resonator consists of half a coconut shell; there are simple forms with only two strings, and more complex ones which have sympathetic strings as well and are decorated with tassles and fabric, the bow may be decorated with bells
[kora, sasong, rebang] Single-string spike fiddle of Flores in Indonesia; the resonator is half a coconut shell, covered with a sago palm-leaf sheath
Wolof term for the single-string fiddle with gourd resonator from Senegambia; soundhole in soundbox, not in soundboard

A ritual music tool; made of a handle (wrapped with string) with three branches, each with a clapper bell; an attribute of ritual wedding figures (marshal, best men); used in the Lubelskie province, Poland; it was shaken to produce ringing to accompany singing

[sason, mbeka, sato] Single-string spike fiddle from Flores, Indonesia. The resonator is half a coconut shell, covered with a leaf; a flat wooden stick is inserted through the resonator and serves as a neck and peg
One-string spike fiddle with gourd resonator of the Moosé in Burkina Faso; noteable performer Nouss Nabil
Cornemuse roussillonnaise
Single-headed open frame drums of the Yoruba people of Nigeria and Benin. It has an earthenware frame and either sticks or bamboo pegs for adjusting tension
Stick zither with one resonator and 5 strings from the Lobi people in Burkina Faso
Flûte oblique de Sumatra

Hindustani classical sarangi: short-necked fiddle, soundbox is made from one piece of wood, covered with skin; membrane is waisted; it has three playing strings and (many) sympathetic strings. Nepali sarangi: small short-necked fiddle made from one piece of wood; the lower part of the soundbox is covered with skin, the upper part is open; it typically has 4 strings; not to be confused with sarinda (see below)
Short-necked bowl fiddle from South Asia; resonator is rounded and deeply waisted, the lower part is covered with skin, while the upper part is open and has the shape of an umbrella
One-string fiddle with tin can resonator at the top end of the Tswana and Xhoisan people from Botswana
Hautbois cylindrique de la province de Sind (Pakistan)
Bell hung on sheep's neck as a signalization (formerly also for apotropaic purposes)
Four-string fiddle of the Han Chinese (si = four)
Compact cylindrical footed drum from the Teke-Kukuya people in the Republic of Congo. Used to accompany the song during the ritual dances and popular festivities
Vessel rattle from Burkia Faso; resonator can be of different forms: woven basked; calebash
Two-stringed spike tube fiddle of Thailand, resembling the Chinese erhu
Two-string fiddle of Laos, with a jackwood or bamboo soundbox
Three-stringed spike fiddle of Thailand, resembling the Javanese rebab; resonator is coconut shell with three bulges on the back, covered with skin
Two-string fiddle of Thailand, with a coconut resonator with a carved out back and skin soundtable
Hautbois des Balkans
Single-string fiddle of the Berbers of southern Morocco, with a round soundbox covered with skin; the peg is inserted laterally and the string runs in an angle over the soundboard
Single-string fiddle from Latvia, with a bladder resonator; it is played vertically

Small polish fiddle. Suka is known thanks to an item from the Biłgoraj area, Poland, shown at the First Polish Music Exhibition in Warsaw in 1888 (written accound by Jan Karłowicz, sketch by Tadeusz Dowgird, 1888, watercolour painting by Wojciech Gerson, 1896); in the second half of the 19th c., and possibly at the beginning of the 20th c. it was used in the south of the Lublin region (Biłgoraj area), probably accompanied by a single-skin drum; now used by artists of the folk revival; suka is played in the vertical position (hung over the shoulder on a string or leaned on the knee); players applied side string shortening (so-called fingernail technique)
Gulmancé term for the Griot lute in Burkina Faso
Tamasheq term for the griot lute in Burkina Faso
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Marka people in Burkina Faso, and the Wolof people in Senegal and the Gambia
Single-string tube fiddle of the Hima in Rwanda and northeastern DR Congo
Fiddle used by the Sundanese and Badui people in West Java, with a trapezoidal resonator. Often has a carved-out pegbox
Newly developed spike fiddle, created by Peter Biffin; there are several types; the instrument resembles a kamanche
Hautbois de Catalogne
Urdu name for the long-necked fretted peacock fiddle in India and Pakistan; in northern India it is known as mayuri
Three-stringed box fiddle of the Inuit people

Wooden double bell of the Kongo-Vili people in the Kouilou region near the Atlantic coast in the Republic of the Congo. Geometrical decoration engraved and burned. Used by the Nganga, healer and spiritualist, the hourglass shaped double bell is liked to Nkisi cult worship and is used during songs and dances to treat the ill. It is also played during twin birth ceremonies
Pair of goblet drum from the Sahel people in Burkina Faso, near the border with Mali
Rectangual raft zither made of straw stems bound together and with the strings cut out from the stems. From the Bwa and Samo people in Burkina Faso
Hautbois de Catalogne
Side-blown flute from the Peul people in Senegal. Named after the cane's name out of which it is made. Mouthpiece made of wax. Often covered in colourful textile
Harp-lute from the Turka people from Burkina Faso. Often with a metal buzzer at the end of the neck
Fulbé term for the double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) in Burkina Faso

Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum), from the Siamou people in Burkina Faso (compared to the other Burkina talking drums there are considerably fewer strings attached to change the tensions of the membranes)
Balafo with 18 lamels from the Toussian people in the west of Burkina Faso

Conical or cylindrical drum of the Teke people of the Plateaux region in Republic of the Congo, made from the holow trunk of a tree, on to one opening of which is nailed an antelope skin. The nails are covered by a strip made from caoutchouc
Single-string spike fiddle of the Baggara people of Sudan

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: Bęben klepsydrowy ze zmiennym napięciem membran
Viool met meetrillende snaren / viool d'amore

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Spike tube fiddle of the Kikuyu people in Kenya
Argyle ocarina from the Yana people in Burkina Faso
Wooden flute from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Wooden flute from the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Small wooden sculptured flute, often in the form of a stylized bird, with fingerholes, and open at the end. From the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Small wooden scultpured flute, often in the form of a stylized bird, with fingerholes, and open at the end. From the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Small wooden sculptured flute, often in the form of a stylized bird, with fingerholes, and open at the end. From the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Small wooden sculptured flute, often in the form of a stylized bird, with fingerholes, and closed at the end. From the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Balafo with 14 lamels from the Pougouly people in Burkina Faso
Whistle, end-blown, stopped at the end and with no fingerholes. Whistle. Often decoartedwith loose hanging strips
Wooden sculptured flute, closed at the end and with fingerholes. From the Nuni people in Burkina Faso
Two-string fiddle of the Han Chinese; resonator is coconut, covered with wooden soundboard; bridge is usually a sea-shell; resembles banhu but pegs are dorsally inserted
Transverse flute from the Gulmancé people in the est of Burkina Faso. Tube in bambou or plastic; often covered with leather. Four fingerholes
Wooden whistle open at the end and with fingerholes. From the Kô people in Burkina Faso
Double-headed hourglass pression drum (also known as the variable tension drum or the talking drum) from the Turka people in Burkina Faso
Strung rattles made of folded palmleaves
General term for fiddle in Central and Eastern Africa
Two-string Chinese fiddle; a 'middle' erhu with an alto range
Small fiddle from the Tatra mountains in Poland
